Coronavirus guidance is being updated.
Read what you can and cannot do

Mauritius has put measures in place to limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19).
For information on how to return to the UK from Mauritius, see Return to the UK
Local Measures
The Mauritian authorities have introduced a number of measures in response to the coronavirus pandemic including imposing restrictions on movements throughout the country, screening processes and a ban on entry by any travellers. This includes returning residents.
On Friday 20 March, the Mauritian authorities imposed restrictions on movements throughout the country. Essential services including supermarkets and pharmacies remain open.
On 1 May, the Mauritian Prime Minister announced an extension to the lockdown until 1 June, with relaxation of some measures on 15 May. Social distancing and wearing of face masks in public remains mandatory. Please follow the advice of the local authorities.
There are currently no regular commercial flights from Mauritius to the UK. For information on how to return to the UK from Mauritius, see Return to the UK.
If you have flights booked to or from Mauritius on a future date, you should contact your airline or tour operator to confirm travel arrangements.
Further information
See the TravelHealthPro website for further advice on travel abroad and reducing spread of respiratory viruses during the COVID-19 pandemic.
